0.9774252772331238, "span": {"begin": 720, "end": 724}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cultured human cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9514954090118408, "span": {"begin": 754, "end": 774}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7513930201530457, "span": {"begin": 763, "end": 768}}, {"id": ["mesh:D045169"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SARS", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.6812438368797302, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 793}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SARS-CoV-2", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7422179579734802, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 799}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "viral RNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.7800798416137695, "span": {"begin": 873, "end": 882}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:340061"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ISGs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9560748934745789, "span": {"begin": 897, "end": 901}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ISGs", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.651689887046814, "span": {"begin": 969, "end": 973}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3438"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IFN-I", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9958866238594055, "span": {"begin": 999, "end": 1004}}], "text": "The functional relationships between the upstream IFN-I antagonism and downstream increase in SARS-CoV-2 viral replication is biologically plausible via the suppression of IFN through interaction inhibition of the host pathway proteins by viral proteins. This in turn would lead to suppressing the expression of ISGs that have been demonstrated to inhibit replication. The effects of ISGs on viral replication has been demonstrated for several viruses (Schoggins et al., 2011). SARS-CoV-2 replication may be impacted by different ISGs than other families of viruses. A gain-of-function analysis evaluating the impacts of ISGs on SARS-CoV-2 viral replication (Martin-Sancho et al., 2021) showed that a specific subset of ISGs when stably overexpressed in cultured human cells infected with SARS-CoV-2 controlled viral infection, including RNA binding proteins that suppress viral RNA synthesis and ISGs inhibiting viral assembly and egress. Therefore, the lack of these ISGs due to antagonism of the IFN-I pathway leads to increased viral replication.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:25:48 +0000 2026"}